import polars as pl

# Path to the input CSV file in Google Colab
file_path_gdp_vs_vacc = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/indicator_2.csv'

# Path to save the output CSV file in the same directory as the input file
output_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/cleaned_ind2_dynamic_fields.csv'

try:
    # Step 1: Read the file into a Polars DataFrame
    df = pl.read_csv(file_path_gdp_vs_vacc)

    # Step 2: Rename the column 'time_period' to 'year', if it exists
    if 'time_period' in df.columns:
        df = df.rename({'time_period': 'year'})

    # Step 3: Identify Dynamic Fields
    # A field is dynamic if it has more than one unique value across rows
    dynamic_fields = [col for col in df.columns if df[col].n_unique() > 1]

    # Step 4: Remove the specified fields
    excluded_fields = ["alpha_2_code", "alpha_3_code", "numeric_code"]
    dynamic_fields = [col for col in dynamic_fields if col not in excluded_fields]

    # Step 5: Check for missing values in each dynamic field
    print("Missing Values in Dynamic Fields:")
    for col in dynamic_fields:
        missing_count = df[col].is_null().sum()
        print(f"Field '{col}' has {missing_count} missing values.")

    # Step 6: Select only dynamic fields
    dynamic_df = df.select(dynamic_fields)

    # Step 7: Save the dynamic fields to a new CSV file
    dynamic_df.write_csv(output_path)

    print("\nDynamic fields saved to:", output_path)

except Exception as e:
    print(f"Failed to process the file: {e}")

import pandas as pd

# Path to the input CSV file in Google Colab
file_path_gdp_vs_vacc = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/metadata.csv'

# Path to save the output CSV file in the same directory as the input file
output_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/cleaned_meta_dynamic_fields.csv'

try:
    # Step 1: Read the file into a Pandas DataFrame
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path_gdp_vs_vacc)

    # Step 2: Identify Dynamic Fields
    # A field is dynamic if it has more than one unique value across rows
    dynamic_fields = [col for col in df.columns if df[col].nunique() > 1]

    # Step 3: Remove the specified fields
    excluded_fields = [
        "alpha_2_code", "alpha_3_code", "numeric_code",
        "Military expenditure (% of GDP)",
        "Fossil fuel energy consumption (% of total)",
        "GDP growth (annual %)",
        "Birth rate, crude (per 1,000 people)",
        "Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)",
        "GNI (current US$)",
        "Inflation, consumer prices (annual %)"
    ]
    dynamic_fields = [col for col in dynamic_fields if col not in excluded_fields]

    # Step 4: Identify and remove countries where relevant fields are fully missing
    countries_with_missing_fields = df.groupby('country').apply(
        lambda x: (
            x['Population, total'].isna().all() or
            x['GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'].isna().all() or
            x['Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'].isna().all()
        )
    )
    removed_countries = countries_with_missing_fields[countries_with_missing_fields].index.tolist()

    # Print the removed countries
    print("Removed countries where one or more relevant fields are fully missing:")
    print(removed_countries)

    # Keep only countries where none of the relevant fields are fully missing
    df = df[~df['country'].isin(removed_countries)]

    # Step 5: Fill missing values for each country with the average value of the field
    fields_to_fill = ['Population, total', 'GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)', 'Life expectancy at birth, total (years)']
    for field in fields_to_fill:
        df[field] = df.groupby('country')[field].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))

    # Step 6: Round values in specified fields to 2 decimal places
    df['GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'] = df['GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'].round(2)
    df['Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'] = df['Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'].round(2)

    # Step 7: Check for missing values in each dynamic field
    print("\nMissing Values in Dynamic Fields:")
    for col in dynamic_fields:
        missing_count = df[col].isna().sum()
        print(f"Field '{col}' has {missing_count} missing values.")

    # Step 8: Select only dynamic fields
    dynamic_df = df[dynamic_fields]

    # Step 9: Save the dynamic fields to a new CSV file
    dynamic_df.to_csv(output_path, index=False)

    print("\nDynamic fields saved to:", output_path)

except Exception as e:
    print(f"Failed to process the file: {e}")

import pandas as pd

# Paths to the input CSV files in Google Colab
main_table_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/cleaned_ind2_dynamic_fields.csv'
secondary_table_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/cleaned_meta_dynamic_fields.csv'

# Path to save the resulting merged table in Google Colab
output_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/filtered_trimmed_table.csv'

try:
    # Step 1: Mount Google Drive if not already mounted
    from google.colab import drive
    drive.mount('/content/drive')

    # Step 2: Read the main and secondary tables into Pandas DataFrames
    main_df = pd.read_csv(main_table_path)
    secondary_df = pd.read_csv(secondary_table_path)

    # Step 3: Filter the secondary table to match countries and years from the main table
    filtered_secondary_df = secondary_df[
        (secondary_df['country'].isin(main_df['country'])) &
        (secondary_df['year'].isin(main_df['year']))
    ]

    # Step 4: Perform an inner join on 'country' and 'year'
    merged_df = pd.merge(main_df, filtered_secondary_df, on=['country', 'year'], how='left')

    # Step 5: Identify countries with insufficient data (all missing values for a field)
    fields_to_check = ['Population, total', 'GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)', 'Life expectancy at birth, total (years)']
    insufficient_data_countries = []

    for field in fields_to_check:
        missing_countries = merged_df.groupby('country')[field].apply(lambda x: x.isna().all())
        insufficient_data_countries.extend(missing_countries[missing_countries].index.tolist())

    # Remove duplicate country names from the list
    insufficient_data_countries = list(set(insufficient_data_countries))
    print("Countries with insufficient data:", insufficient_data_countries)

    # Remove rows corresponding to these countries
    filtered_merged_df = merged_df[~merged_df['country'].isin(insufficient_data_countries)]

    # Step 6: Remove strings after commas for all string values in each row
    def remove_after_comma(cell):
        if isinstance(cell, str) and ',' in cell:
            return cell.split(',')[0]  # Retain only the part before the comma
        return cell

    filtered_merged_df = filtered_merged_df.applymap(remove_after_comma)

    # Step 7: Check for missing values in all columns after processing
    print("\nMissing Values in All Columns After Processing:")
    for col in filtered_merged_df.columns:
        missing_count = filtered_merged_df[col].isna().sum()
        print(f"Column '{col}' has {missing_count} missing values.")

    # Step 8: Save the processed table to a new CSV file
    filtered_merged_df.to_csv(output_path, index=False)

    print("\nProcessed table saved to:", output_path)

except Exception as e:
    print(f"Failed to process the files: {e}")

import pandas as pd

# Path to the input CSV file
input_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/filtered_trimmed_table.csv'

# Path to save the output CSV file with the new field
output_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/filtered_trimmed_with_popvacc.csv'

try:
    # Step 1: Read the input file into a Pandas DataFrame
    df = pd.read_csv(input_path)

    # Step 2: Calculate the absolute value of vaccinated individuals using 'obs_value'
    # Add the new field 'popvacc' to the DataFrame
    df['popvacc'] = (df['obs_value'] / 100) * df['Population, total']

    # Step 3: Round 'popvacc' to the nearest integer
    df['popvacc'] = df['popvacc'].round(0).astype(int)

    # Step 4: Save the updated DataFrame to a new CSV file
    df.to_csv(output_path, index=False)

    print("Updated table with 'popvacc' saved to:", output_path)

except Exception as e:
    print(f"Failed to process the file: {e}")

import pandas as pd

# Path to the input CSV file
input_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/filtered_trimmed_table.csv'

# Path to save the output CSV file with the new fields
output_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/filtered_trimmed_with_averages.csv'

try:
    # Step 1: Read the input file into a Pandas DataFrame
    df = pd.read_csv(input_path)

    # Step 2: Calculate the percentage of the 'Population, total' field represented by 'obs_value'
    # Add the new field 'popvacc' to the DataFrame
    df['popvacc'] = (df['obs_value'] / 100) * df['Population, total']

    # Step 3: Round 'popvacc' to the nearest integer
    df['popvacc'] = df['popvacc'].round(0).astype(int)

    # Step 4: Calculate averages by country
    df['avg_obs_value'] = df.groupby('country')['obs_value'].transform('mean').round(2)
    df['avg_popvacc'] = df.groupby('country')['popvacc'].transform('mean').round(0).astype(int)
    df['avg_GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'] = df.groupby('country')['GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'].transform('mean').round(2)
    df['avg_Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'] = df.groupby('country')['Life expectancy at birth, total (years)'].transform('mean').round(2)

    # Step 5: Save the updated DataFrame to a new CSV file
    df.to_csv(output_path, index=False)

    print("Updated table with averages saved to:", output_path)

except Exception as e:
    print(f"Failed to process the file: {e}")

try:
    # Step 1: Read the input file into a Pandas DataFrame
    df = pd.read_csv(input_path)

    # Step 2: Select distinct 'country' and 'avg_obs_value'
    df_ranking = df[['country', 'avg_obs_value']].drop_duplicates()

    # Step 3: Sort the DataFrame by 'avg_obs_value' in descending order
    df_ranking = df_ranking.sort_values(by='avg_obs_value', ascending=False)

    # Step 4: Rename the field 'avg_obs_value' to 'AVG%'
    df_ranking = df_ranking.rename(columns={'avg_obs_value': 'AVG%'})

    # Step 5: Get the top 10 countries by 'AVG%'
    top_10_df = df_ranking.head(10)

    # Step 6: Get the last 10 countries by 'AVG%'
    last_10_df = df_ranking.tail(10)

    # Step 7: Save the top 10 and last 10 DataFrames to separate CSV files
    top_10_df.to_csv(top_10_output_path, index=False)
    last_10_df.to_csv(last_10_output_path, index=False)

    print("Top 10 sorted countries saved to:", top_10_output_path)
    print("Last 10 sorted countries saved to:", last_10_output_path)

except Exception as e:

import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd

# Mount Google Drive
from google.colab import drive
drive.mount('/content/drive', force_remount=True)

# Step 1: Load the World Map Geometry
shapefile_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/natural_earth/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp"
world = gpd.read_file(shapefile_path)

# Ensure geometries are valid
if not world.geometry.is_valid.all():
    world.geometry = world.geometry.buffer(0)  # Fix invalid geometries

# Step 2: Load Your Data
data_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/filtered_trimmed_with_averages.csv"
data = pd.read_csv(data_path)

# Ensure 'avg_obs_value' exists instead of 'AVG%' if column renaming has not been applied
if 'avg_obs_value' in data.columns and 'AVG%' not in data.columns:
    data = data.rename(columns={'avg_obs_value': 'AVG%'})  # Rename 'avg_obs_value' to 'AVG%'

# Step 3: Merge the Data
merged = world.merge(data, left_on='NAME', right_on='country', how='left')

# Step 4: Extract Coordinates for Each Country
# Use the original GeoDataFrame's geometry
if 'geometry' in merged.columns:
    merged['long'] = merged.geometry.bounds.minx
    merged['lat'] = merged.geometry.bounds.miny
else:
    print("Warning: No geometry column found. Skipping coordinate extraction.")
    merged['long'], merged['lat'] = None, None

# Step 5: Drop Rows with Missing 'country' Values
cleaned_df = merged.dropna(subset=['country'])

# Step 6: Ensure Distinct 'country' Values with Lat/Long and AVG%
if 'AVG%' in cleaned_df.columns:
    distinct_df = cleaned_df[['country', 'lat', 'long', 'AVG%']].drop_duplicates()
else:
    raise KeyError("'AVG%' column is missing in the cleaned DataFrame.")

# Print the cleaned data as a table
print("Cleaned Data (Distinct Countries with Lat/Long and AVG%):")
print(distinct_df.to_string(index=False))

# Step 7: Save the Cleaned Data to CSV
cleaned_csv_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/cleaned_distinct_country_lat_long_avg.csv"
distinct_df.to_csv(cleaned_csv_path, index=False)

print(f"\nCleaned data with lat/long and AVG% saved to '{cleaned_csv_path}'")

import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set file paths
shapefile_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/natural_earth/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp'
data_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/cleaned_distinct_country_lat_long_avg.csv'

# Load the world map and your cleaned data
world = gpd.read_file(shapefile_path)
df = pd.read_csv(data_path)

# Create GeoDataFrame
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(df['long'], df['lat']))

# Randomly sample 15% of the countries
sampled_countries = gdf.sample(frac=0.15, random_state=42)  # Set random_state for reproducibility

# Plot the map
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(14, 10))  # Adjust figure size for clarity
world.boundary.plot(ax=ax, linewidth=1, edgecolor="black")  # Plot world boundaries

# Plot heat map with bubbles
gdf.plot(
    ax=ax,
    column="AVG%",  # Color intensity based on AVG%
    cmap="YlOrRd",  # Color map: Yellow, Orange, Red
    markersize=gdf["AVG%"] * 3,  # Bubble size scaled to AVG%
    alpha=0.6,  # Transparency of bubbles
    legend=True
)

# Add labels for sampled countries
for x, y, label in zip(sampled_countries.geometry.x, sampled_countries.geometry.y, sampled_countries['country']):
    ax.text(
        x, y, label,
        fontsize=8,  # Font size for labels
        color="black",
        ha="center",
        bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.5, edgecolor='none')  # White background for text
    )

# Set the title and display the map
plt.title("Global 3rd dose DTP- Vaccination Trends (1980-2023)", fontsize=16)
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_line, geom_point, labs, theme_minimal, theme, element_line, scale_x_continuous, scale_y_continuous

# Mount Google Drive
from google.colab import drive
drive.mount('/content/drive')

# File Path
file_path_gdp_vs_vacc = '/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/sub_df5.csv'

# Load CSV File
df = pd.read_csv(file_path_gdp_vs_vacc)

# Handle Missing Values
df['avg_gdp'] = df['avg_gdp'].fillna(df['avg_gdp'].median())
df['AVG%'] = df['AVG%'].fillna(df['AVG%'].median())
df['AVG_liftexpact'] = df['AVG_liftexpact'].fillna(df['AVG_liftexpact'].median())

# Sort DataFrame
df = df.sort_values(by="avg_gdp")

# Random Sampling
bubble_df = df.sample(n=30, random_state=42)

# Categorize Life Expectancy
def assign_size_category(value):
    return "Small (â¤60)" if value <= 60 else "Large (>60)"

bubble_df["bubble_size_category"] = bubble_df["AVG_liftexpact"].apply(assign_size_category)
size_mapping = {"Small (â¤60)": 8, "Large (>60)": 12}  # Adjusted Sizes
bubble_df["bubble_size"] = bubble_df["bubble_size_category"].map(size_mapping)

# Quadratic Fit
coefficients = np.polyfit(df["avg_gdp"], df["AVG%"], deg=2)
quadratic_fit = np.poly1d(coefficients)
df["smoothed_y"] = quadratic_fit(df["avg_gdp"])

# Plot Creation
plot = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x="avg_gdp")) +
    geom_line(aes(y="smoothed_y"), color="blue", size=1.5) +  # Quadratic Line
    geom_point(
        data=bubble_df,
        mapping=aes(y="AVG%", fill="bubble_size_category"),
        size=12,  # Bubble Size
        color="green",
        alpha=0.5  # Increased Transparency
    ) +
    labs(
        title="Relationship between GDP and AVG%",
        x="Average GDP (USD)",
        y="AVG% (Percentage)",
        fill="Life Expectancy Categories"
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits=(0, 10000)) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks=np.linspace(df["AVG%"].min(), df["AVG%"].max(), 10)) +  # Adjusted Breaks
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        legend_position="right",
        panel_grid_major=element_line(size=1.5, color="grey"),
        panel_grid_minor=element_line(size=1, color="lightgrey")
    )
)

# Display Plot
plot  # Render directly in Colab
